  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (synthetic adversarial: software fault coverage gap)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). The CFD pipeline is implemented as a multi-stage software system: a Python-based pre-processor constructs boundary conditions and mesh partitioning, a parallelised finite-volume solver (OpenFOAM 9) integrates the modified Power-Law hemolysis transport equation across rotating reference frames, and a post-processing module aggregates per-cell damage accumulation into the relative hemolysis index. All validation runs reported nominal completion with converged residuals. A single solver restart event during grid-independence testing was attributed to a transient I/O collision on the HPC cluster and was resolved by re-submission; no further investigation of concurrency behaviour was performed. The dominant numerical failure modes of the hemolysis transport — including potential NaN propagation when local shear stress approaches zero in near-wall recirculation zones, floating-point overflow in the exponentiated damage integral at high impeller speeds, and thread-level race conditions in the OpenMP reduction of the global damage accumulator — were not exercised during any validation activity. All ValidationResults record nominal completion under well-conditioned operating points, leaving these software fault pathways unvalidated.",
  "assuranceLevel": "Medium",
  "decision": "Accepted",
  "deviceClass": "Class II",
  "modelRiskLevel": 2,
  "couName": "CPB use",
